<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">The subtribe is identified and separated according to the following list of characters:</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Hindwing trilobate, strongly notched at CuA2 with CuP-Pcu-A1 lobe slightly longer, as wide as Sc-R-MP-CuA lobe.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Posterior margin distinctly notched at A1 2.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Anal lobe posterior to A1 present, surpassing half-length of CuP-Pcu-A1 lobe, apically rounded and 1/2 thinner than the anterior ones, and with margins sub-parallel.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Sc-R-MP-CuA and CuP-Pcu-A1 lobes covered with a set of numerous transverse veins.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">CuA and CuP merging at the anterior notch.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Pcu and A1 merging in basal half of forewing.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">A2 present, single.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="69" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="69">
This subtribe is currently monogeneric and distributed in Indonesia (Sumatra), in Peninsular Malaysia and Sarawak (
<bibRefCitation author="Gnezdilov, VM" journalOrPublisher="Arthropod Systematics &amp; Phylogeny" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="101 - 108" refId="B29" refString="Gnezdilov, VM, Wilson, MR, 2007. Review of the genus Scantinius Stal with notes on the tribe Parahiraciini Cheng &amp; Yang (Hemiptera: Auchenorrhyncha: Fulgoroidea: Issidae). Arthropod Systematics &amp; Phylogeny 65: 101 - 108" title="Review of the genus Scantinius Stal with notes on the tribe Parahiraciini Cheng &amp; Yang (Hemiptera: Auchenorrhyncha: Fulgoroidea: Issidae)." volume="65" year="2007">Gnezdilov and Wilson 2007</bibRefCitation>
). Based on the strong CuA2-CuP notch and the reticulated Sc-R-MP-CuA and CuP-Pcu-A1 lobes, it is tentatively considered as a sister lineage to 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Tropiduchidae" genus="Parahiraciina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Parahiraciina</taxonomicName>
, but without molecular data, its place in the phylogeny of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melichar" authorityYear="1906" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Hemisphaeriinae">Hemisphaeriinae</taxonomicName>
sec. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2016.08.012" author="Wang, ML" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="69" pagination="224 - 234" refId="B39" refString="Wang, ML, Zhang, YL, Bourgoin, T, 2016. Planthopper family Issidae (Insecta: Hemiptera: Fulgoromorpha): linking molecular phylogeny with classification. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 105: 224 - 234, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2016.08.012" title="Planthopper family Issidae (Insecta: Hemiptera: Fulgoromorpha): linking molecular phylogeny with classification." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ympev.2016.08.012" volume="105" year="2016">Wang et al. (2016)</bibRefCitation>
remains uncertain.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
